Growing up in South Asian culture , I was always surrounded by beauty standards that emphasised fair skin, slender figures, and long, dark hair. These ideals were everywhere – in the media, from family, and just in society in general. It made me feel like I had to fit into a specific mold, which really impacted my self-esteem and sense of identity. Mix that with going to school with girls that looked nothing like me, it was mental mayhem!

But things are changing now. Thanks to body positivity movements and more diverse representation in media, those narrow standards are being challenged. There are lots of conversations being had and this is so important to make changes to our own beauty standards, which I know is always a difficult realisation to have. 

For my two daughters, I’m determined to create a different experience. I want them to grow up knowing that their worth isn’t tied to how they look, and to celebrate their unique beauty and individuality. I know they will be faced with new and possibly very different standards to what I was facing, but I’m trying to make sure they have a strong sense of self, so those inflictions do not matter. 

While those old beauty standards shaped my past, the evolving landscape has allowed me to redefine beauty for myself and my family. I hope we continue to get better at celebrating diversity and encouraging self-acceptance. 

