A quick follow-up from my previous post for my new followers (hi and welcome!) As I mentioned, it is best to get your acne under control before tackling hyperpigmentation. Here’s a quick breakdown of some acne ingredients you can use:

~ Benzoyl peroxide: kills acne-causing bacteria and is best for inflamed acne.

~ Salicylic acid (BHA): penetrates into the skin and unclogs pores. Works best for congested skin (whiteheads and blackheads, both also known as comedones).

~ Lactic acid (AHAs): exfoliates the top layer of the skin which improves skin texture. A good choice for rough, bumpy skin.

~ Azelaic acid: kills acne-causing bacteria and helps to exfoliate dead skin cells that often clog pores and trigger breakouts. A great choice for comedones and mild to moderate inflamed acne. 

~ Niacinamide: reduces the overproduction of oil which clogs pores. Also an anti-inflammatory ingredient that works to reduce the swelling associated with acne. Prevents comedonal acne and is a good (supplementary) ingredient for mild to moderate inflamed acne.

~ Retinal (retinoids): accelerates skin cell turnover which helps to unclog pores. Also a great anti-inflammatory ingredient. A great choice for comedonal acne and inflamed acne (with consistent use and patience).

~ Sulphur (not pictured): works by inhibiting the growth of acne-causing bacteria. A good option for comedones and mild to moderate acne. 

And that’s it! You can get most of these ingredients over the counter. Please note that you don’t have to use all of them. Find the ones that work for you and stick with them. 

Finally, consider seeing a professional if you’re not seeing progress!

